04511nam a22006135i 9780773563063DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735630637 a10.1515/97807735630632doi  a(DE-B1597)657717  a(OCoLC)732600973  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1455.M38bK46 1991eb 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a305.42/0921 aKinnear, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMargaret McWilliams :bAn Interwar Feminist /cMary Kinnear. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMargaret McWilliams: An Interwar Feminist -- tFoundations -- tInitial Forays -- tThe First Decade -- t“Education in All Its Phases” -- tGeography and History -- tPolitics -- tGovernment House -- tMargaret McWilliams, Women, and Feminists -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMcWilliams began her career in public life when she arrived in Winnipeg at the age of thirty-five. A graduate in Political Science from the University of Toronto, she had a vision of women university graduates as "pilgrims of peace abroad and pilgrims of understanding at home." During her years in Winnipeg she became the first president of the Canadian Federation of University Women, wrote a number of books on history and politics, served as a city councillor during the Depression, and in 1943 chaired the subcommittee on Postwar Problems for Women for the federal government's committee on Reconstruction. For more than thirty years she held regular "current events" classes, providing education in politics for women. Central to Kinnear's study is a definition of feminism with three core components: women are equal to men and ought not to be treated as inferior; the condition of women is socially constructed and can be altered by human choice; and women experience a consciousness of identification with other women as a social group. Any definition of feminism is bound to be contentious but one is necessary, Kinnear maintains, if comparisons are to be made over time and across cultures. Kinnear also discusses the notion of class and its relationship to gender and ethnicity in the interwar period. Margaret McWilliams is being published during the seventy-fifth anniversary of the enfranchisement of women in Manitoba, Saskatchewan, and Alberta, the first provinces to do so. Margaret McWilliams, the woman, was an exemplary model of women in post-suffrage public life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeministsxBiographyxCanada. 0aFeministszCanadavBiography. 0aFéministesxBiographiesxCanada. 0aRéformateurs sociauxxBiographiesxCanada. 0aRéformatrices socialesxBiographiesxCanadaxCanada. 0aSocial reformersxBiographyxCanada. 0aSocial reformerszCanadavBiography. 0aWomen social reformersxBiographyxCanada. 0aWomen social reformerszCanadavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356306340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563063/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles